<h2>The question</h2>
<p>
  The <a href="/backlog/1403-discovery-lens-data-lifecycle-paradigms-load-cache-mutate-sy/">data-lifecycle
  lens</a> surfaced the <strong>write-path / realtime</strong> half of the data lifecycle as unowned, naming
  four sub-concerns: <strong>(1)</strong> an offline mutation <strong>queue + replay</strong> on reconnect
  (the inverse of the read-path cache <a href="/backlog/1419-server-state-query-cache-lifecycle-fetch-dedupe-cache-stalen/">#1419</a>);
  <strong>(2)</strong> <strong>realtime subscription / live-update</strong>; <strong>(3)</strong>
  <strong>conflict resolution</strong> (last-write-wins / merge / CRDT); <strong>(4)</strong>
  <strong>presence / collaboration</strong>. The filed crux: <strong>ONE <code>sync</code> intent</strong>
  spanning all four, vs <strong>splitting</strong> offline-sync from realtime-collaboration (different actor
  models &mdash; self-over-time vs many-at-once), vs <strong>a conflict-resolution behavior</strong> reusable
  by both.
</p>

<h2>Finding 0 (load-bearing) — this is NOT greenfield; three of the four sub-concerns already have ratified WE homes</h2>
<p>
  The card's premise (&ldquo;none owns the sync/conflict contract&rdquo;) is <strong>largely false</strong>.
  WE has already decomposed this exact problem, and the <code>storage</code> protocol summary states the
  decomposition verbatim: <em>&ldquo;the durable outbox/replay is webreliability, and conflict-merge is the
  change-tracking protocol's sync dimension &mdash; each tracked under its own owner&rdquo;</em>
  (<code>src/_data/protocols/storage.json:4</code>, ratified from #011).
</p>
