  </tbody>
</table>
</we-data-table>
<p>
  So the question is not &ldquo;where does a homeless sync standard live.&rdquo; It is: should WE mint a
  <em>new</em> orchestration owner that <em>composes</em> these four ratified homes, or is offline-first sync
  simply their <strong>composition</strong> (no new artifact)? The same reframe
  <a href="/backlog/1395-optimistic-mutation-apply-reconcile-rollback-standard-placem/">#1395</a> and
  <a href="/backlog/1398-progressive-loading-skeleton-streaming-progressive-hydration/">#1398</a> (progressive-loading
  = composition over existing homes, no new standard) both hit.
</p>

<h2>Finding 1 — leading systems treat offline-sync and realtime-collab as SEPARATE composable layers, not ONE primitive</h2>
<p>
  The card's first key question &mdash; do the leaders treat offline-sync and realtime-collab as ONE
  primitive or TWO? &mdash; the survey answers <strong>decisively: separate, composable layers</strong>, with
  conflict-resolution a <em>third</em> swappable thing under both:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Liveblocks</strong> decomposes a room into <strong>distinct primitives: Presence, Broadcast,
    Storage, Threads</strong> &mdash; presence (ephemeral) is a different primitive from durable storage and
    from broadcast.</li>
  <li><strong>PowerSync</strong> separates a persistent <strong>upload queue</strong> (FIFO + retry +
    checkpoints) from the read sync-stream, and <strong>leaves conflict resolution to your backend</strong>.</li>
  <li><strong>TanStack Query</strong> ships offline mutation persistence (pause &rarr; dehydrate &rarr;
    <code>resumePausedMutations()</code>) &mdash; queue + replay, and <strong>not a CRDT model at all</strong>.</li>
  <li><strong>Replicache</strong> uses mutator + push/pull/poke + <strong>server-authoritative rebase</strong>
    &mdash; distinct from CRDT merge.</li>
  <li><strong>CRDTs (Yjs / Automerge)</strong> are a swappable <strong>merge algorithm</strong> with idempotent
    exactly-once replay; the queue + transport around them is the same regardless of merge strategy.</li>
  <li><strong>PartyKit</strong> is transport-only &mdash; &ldquo;integrate Yjs yourself.&rdquo;</li>
</ul>
<p>
  The convergent factoring &mdash; <strong>(a) transport, (b) write outbox/queue with replay, (c) swappable
  conflict-merge strategy, (d) presence/awareness</strong> &mdash; maps <strong>one-to-one</strong> onto WE's
  already-ratified homes. The single <code>sync</code> intent is the <strong>broken</strong> branch (it fuses
  four orthogonal, already-homed axes); &ldquo;a conflict-resolution behavior reusable by both&rdquo; is
  <strong>already true</strong> (<code>change-tracking</code>'s <code>CustomChangeStrategy</code>).
</p>

<h2>Finding 2 — the two actor models ARE different end-states, but the split is along EXISTING seams</h2>
<p>
  <strong>self-over-time</strong> (offline-first) = durable outbox (webreliability) + a checkpoint/cursor +
  replay on <code>online</code> + the <code>mutation</code> apply/rollback lifecycle; conflict =
  server-authoritative rebase or LWW. <strong>many-at-once</strong> (realtime-collab) = a live transport
  (webrealtime) + a shared document with a <em>concurrent</em> merge strategy (change-tracking CRDT/OT) +
  <strong>presence</strong> (ephemeral, never persisted). They share the merge-strategy contract and the
  transport but differ in actor model &mdash; and <em>neither needs a new owner</em>. Fusing them would force
  one artifact to span an ephemeral presence channel, a durable outbox, a transport negotiation, and a merge
  algorithm &mdash; four axes WE keeps in four homes (the orthogonality break #1318/#1324/#1337 found one
  intent over; the homonym trap #1395 untangled on <code>loader.strategy.optimistic</code>).
</p>

<h2>Finding 3 — presence/collaboration UX is a thin render intent; the primitive partly already ships</h2>
<p>
  &ldquo;Who-else-is-here / live cursors&rdquo; splits into <strong>transport</strong> (webrealtime, ephemeral
  awareness), <strong>presence state</strong> (a roster of peers), and <strong>render</strong> (avatars /
  cursors / &ldquo;X is editing&rdquo;). The render is a UX intent;
  <a href="/intents/live-region-status/">live-region-status</a> already announces a <em>local</em> presence
  change, and a dedicated presence/roster intent could own the multi-peer roster UX. The co-edit presence
  primitive <strong>already exists</strong>: <code>CoEditCoordinator</code>
  (<code>draft-persistence.json:54,88</code>) surfaces &ldquo;X also editing&rdquo; over BroadcastChannel and
  <strong>explicitly does not merge state</strong> &mdash; detection and policy already separated.
</p>

<h2>Finding 4 — WE precedent is unanimous: compose existing homes, mint only the thin missing seam</h2>
<p>
  #455 (transport homed by purpose), #011 (outbox &rarr; webreliability, conflict-merge &rarr;
  change-tracking, named explicitly), #1395 (the <code>mutation</code> intent; running queue stays FUI),
  #1419 (the read-path <code>query</code> cache a mutation invalidates), and #1398 (progressive-loading ruled
  a composition over existing homes, <strong>no new standard</strong>). The unanimous move: <strong>name the
  orthogonal axis in its own home; compose, don't fuse.</strong> The only thing that could be new is a
  <strong>thin orchestration seam</strong> sequencing the four homes (queue &rarr; detect conflict &rarr;
  pick strategy &rarr; transport-publish &rarr; replay) &mdash; gated on <code>storage.json:4</code>'s own
  bar: <em>&ldquo;graduate into a webpersistence project only if a real cross-cutting sync-orchestration
  consumer appears.&rdquo;</em>
</p>

<h2>Classification (per-fork pass)</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Layer</strong> &mdash; <em>no single layer</em>: transport = Protocol (webrealtime), outbox =
    Protocol (webreliability) + Intent (<code>mutation</code>), merge = Protocol (change-tracking), presence =
    Intent + Protocol. A <code>sync</code> <em>intent</em> spanning all four is a category error (mixes
    protocol interop with UX).</li>
  <li><strong>Protocol vs dimension</strong> &mdash; swappable pieces (transport, merge, storage) = Protocols
    (the lock); author-facing pieces (apply strategy, presence render) = Intent dimensions.</li>
  <li><strong>DI-injectable</strong> &mdash; yes, three-fold and already so:
    <code>CustomTransportProvider</code>, <code>CustomChangeStrategy</code>,
    <code>CustomStorageStrategy</code>/<code>CustomRecoveryHandler</code> &mdash; the minimize-lock-in win
    (swappable strategy + transport, not a baked &ldquo;sync engine&rdquo;).</li>
  <li><strong>Default</strong> &mdash; conflict = <strong>last-write-wins</strong> (already
    <code>resolveLww</code>); CRDT is the opt-in. Apply = <strong>pessimistic</strong> (inherited from
    <code>mutation</code>). Replay = FIFO + idempotent exactly-once (fixed mechanics).</li>
  <li><strong>Seams</strong> &mdash; #1419 <code>query</code> cache &middot; #1395 <code>mutation</code>
    &middot; <code>change-tracking</code> &middot; <code>webrealtime</code> &middot;
    <code>webreliability</code> &middot; <code>broadcast</code> &middot; <code>reliability</code>.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The prepared forks</h2>
<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>Crux (single-vs-split) &rarr; SPLIT, decisively.</strong> The single <code>sync</code> intent is
    the <strong>broken</strong> branch (fuses four orthogonal, already-homed axes; mixes protocol with UX).
    &ldquo;A conflict-resolution behavior reusable by both&rdquo; is <strong>already realized</strong> as
    <code>change-tracking</code>'s <code>CustomChangeStrategy</code>.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Fork 1 &mdash; a thin sync-orchestration seam, or no new artifact?</strong> Mint a thin
    <code>sync</code> orchestration intent that <em>composes</em> the four homes + adds only replay-on-reconnect
    choreography <em>(recommended only if a real consumer appears)</em>, vs <strong>no new WE artifact</strong>
    &mdash; offline-first sync = pure composition, the #1398 outcome <em>(recommended default)</em>.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Fork 2 (only if a seam is minted) &mdash; does presence/collaboration ride it or stay its own
    render intent?</strong> Its own intent <em>(recommended, bias-to-separation)</em> &mdash; presence is
    ephemeral render, structurally unlike a durable replay queue.
  </li>
</ul>

